/*
    test_verb_global_name_collision.bgl
    Regression: when a global variable and a global object (or verb, which
    is `alias class verb for object`) share the same lowercased name —
    Beguile is case-insensitive — bare references used to error with
    "X is ambiguous". Both live at global scope so no scope qualifier
    distinguishes them; the only differentiator is type.

    Surfaced from the I6 standard library binding's `extern int score;` +
    `extern verb Score { .score }` collision (cloak-of-darkness used
    `score++` and got the error).

    Resolution: non-object candidate beats object candidate as a last-
    resort tiebreaker. Runs AFTER memberHint and expected-type filters so
    objects are still reachable in their natural contexts:
      - `action == V` (LHS gives expected type → verb wins)
      - `V.method()` (memberHint picks the object)
      - `func(V)` where param is verb-typed (expected type → verb wins)
    Bare references like `score++` with no context default to the variable.

    Trade-off documented: if someone adds operator++ to a verb (rare),
    bare `name++` won't reach the verb when a same-named variable also
    exists. Workaround: rename one of them.

    Mirrors the existing "globals beat enum values" precedent.
*/
#beguilerSettings { target = z5; informName = "none"; outputPath = "tests/output"; }

extern verb action;
extern verb doNothing { .donothing }
extern verb myInt { .myint }
extern int myInt;

void main(){
    // Bare reference resolves to the int (non-verb beats verb).
    myInt = 5;
    myInt++;
    print(myInt);

    // Comparison context: expected type is `verb` (from action), so the
    // verb candidate is the one that survives the type-compatibility filter.
    if(action == doNothing) print("got doNothing");
}
